Section 1:
1 L.D. 1776
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
4 STATE OF MAINE
5 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
6 132ND LEGISLATURE
7 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
8 HOUSE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1187, L.D. 1776, “An Act to Establish the
9 Interdisciplinary Advisory Board for the State House Complex”
10 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
11 'Resolve, to Study the Feasibility of Establishing Environmental Management System
12 Protocols to Address Occupational Health and Safety Within the State House
13 Complex'
14 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
15 'Sec. 1. Environmental Management System Protocols Working Group.
16 Resolved: That the Environmental Management System Protocols Working Group,
17 referred to in this resolve as "the working group," is established to study the feasibility of
18 establishing environmental management system protocols to address the occupational
19 health and safety of Legislators, legislative and executive branch staff and the public within
20 the State House complex.
21 Sec. 2. Working group membership. Resolved: That, notwithstanding Joint
22 Rule 353, the working group membership is as follows:
23 1. Four members of the Senate appointed by the President of the Senate, including 2
24 members from each of the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats in the Legislature;
25 2. Four members of the House of Representatives appointed by the Speaker of the
26 House, including 2 members from each of the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats
27 in the Legislature;
28 3. A member representing an association of executive branch and other public
29 employees, appointed by the President of the Senate;
30 4. A member representing a state indoor air quality organization, appointed by the
31 President of the Senate;
32 5. A member representing an international society of heating, refrigerating and air-
33 conditioning professionals who is a mechanical engineer, appointed by the President of the
34 Senate;
35 6. A member representing occupational health and safety professionals, appointed by
36 the President of the Senate;
Page 1 - 132LR2217(03)
HOUSE AMENDMENT
HOUSE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1187, L.D. 1776
1 7. A member representing a registered lobby with knowledge or expertise in public
2 health, appointed by the Speaker of the House;
3 8. A member representing the Board of Occupational Safety and Health, as established
4 by Title 5, section 12004-G, subsection 24, appointed by the Speaker of the House;
5 9. A member who is an architect with historic architectural experience who is
6 associated with a national professional organization for licensed architects and other
7 construction industry professionals, appointed by the Speaker of the House;
8 10. A member representing a historic preservation organization in the State, appointed
9 by the Speaker of the House; and
10 11. The Director of the Bureau of General Services within the Department of
11 Administrative and Financial Services or the director's designee.
12 Sec. 3. Chairs. Resolved: That the Director of the Bureau of General Services
13 within the Department of Administrative and Financial Services or the director's designee
14 and the member representing the Board of Occupational Safety and Health, as established
15 by Title 5, section 12004-G, subsection 24, serve as cochairs of the working group.
16 Sec. 4. Appointments; convening of working group. Resolved: That all
17 appointments must be made no later than 30 days following the effective date of this
18 resolve. The appointing authorities shall notify the Executive Director of the Legislative
19 Council once all appointments have been completed. After appointment of all members,
20 the chairs shall call and convene the first meeting of the working group. If 30 days or more
21 after the effective date of this resolve a majority of but not all appointments have been
22 made, the chairs may request authority and the Legislative Council may grant authority for
23 the working group to meet and conduct its business.
24 Sec. 5. Compensation. Resolved: That, notwithstanding Joint Rule 353, members
25 of the working group may not be compensated for their work on the working group, but
26 legislative members may receive the legislative per diem.
27 Sec. 6. Duties. Resolved: That the working group shall study the feasibility of
28 establishing environmental management system protocols for identifying and assessing
29 environmental health concerns related the occupational health and safety of Legislators,
30 legislative and executive branch staff and the public within the State House complex. The
31 environmental management system protocols may include, but are not limited to, a
32 framework for identifying and assessing environmental health concerns, implementing
33 environmental improvement action, informing budget decisions related to the
34 implementing of suggestions made by the working group and monitoring and evaluating
35 activities directed toward achieving goals identified by the working group. For purposes
36 of this resolve, "environmental management system" means a system described in "ISO
37 14001, Environmental management systems" published by the International Organization
38 for Standardization.
39 Sec. 7. Staff assistance. Resolved: That the Department of Labor shall provide
40 necessary staffing services to the working group.
41 Sec. 8. Report. Resolved: That, no later than December 3, 2025, the working group
42 shall submit a report that includes its findings and recommendations, including suggested
43 legislation, to the State House facilities committee. The State House facilities committee
Page 2 - 132LR2217(03)
HOUSE AMENDMENT
HOUSE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1187, L.D. 1776
414 may submit legislation based on the findings and recommendations in the report to the
425 Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.'
3 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
4 number to read consecutively.
5 SUMMARY
66 This amendment changes the bill to a resolve. It establishes the Environmental
77 Management System Protocols Working Group to study the feasibility of establishing
88 environmental management system protocols to address the occupational health and safety
99 of Legislators, legislative and executive branch staff and the public within the State House
1100 complex. The working group is required to submit a report that includes its findings and
1111 recommendations to the State House facilities committee, which is authorized to submit
1122 legislation related to the report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
1133 SPONSORED BY: ___________________________________
1144 (Representative MONTELL, K.)
1155 TOWN: Gardiner
Page 3 - 132LR2217(03)
HOUSE AMENDMENT
